05241nam a22008535i 9780674276413DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742764137 a10.4159/97806742764132doi  a(DE-B1597)624079  a(OCoLC)1321743692  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aSD397.D32 7aPOL0440002bisacsh04a634.9/73223/eng/202111221 aZhu, Annah Lake, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRosewood :bEndangered Species Conservation and the Rise of Global China /cAnnah Lake Zhu. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: China’s most valued commodity -- t1 • cultural bloom, cultural boom -- t2 • Hot money capitalism -- t3 • Taking back the forest -- t4 • Worst-case conservation -- t5 • Speculating in species -- t6 • Pluralizing environmentalism -- tConclusion: global Chinas of past and present -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA riveting study of the booming rosewood trade between China and Madagascar uncovers an alternative approach to environmentalism that disrupts Western models. Rosewood is the world’s most trafficked endangered species by value, accounting for larger outlays than ivory, rhino horn, and big cats put together. Nearly all rosewood logs are sent to China, fueling a $26 billion market for classically styled furniture. Vast expeditions across Asia and Africa search for the majestic timber, and legions of Chinese ships sail for Madagascar, where rosewood is purchased straight from the forest. The international response has been to interdict the trade, but in this incisive account Annah Lake Zhu suggests that environmentalists have misunderstood both the intent and the effect of China’s appetite for rosewood, causing social and ecological damage in the process. For one thing, Chinese consumers are understandably seeking to reclaim their cultural heritage, restoring a centuries-old tradition of home furnishing that the Cultural Revolution had condemned. In addition, Chinese firms are investing in environmental preservation. Far from simply exploiting the tree, businesses are carefully managing valuable forests and experimenting with extensive new plantings. This sustainable-use paradigm differs dramatically from the conservation norms preferred by Western-dominated NGOs, whose trade bans have prompted speculation and high prices, even encouraging criminal activity. Meanwhile, attempts to arm conservation task forces—militias meant to guard the forests—have backfired. Drawing on years of fieldwork in China and Madagascar, Rosewood upends the pieties of the global aid industry. Zhu offers a rigorous look at what environmentalism and biodiversity protection might look like in a world no longer dominated by the West.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aDalbergiaxConservationzChina. 0aDalbergiazChina. 0aForest conservationzChina. 0aRosewood (Wood)zChina. 0aRosewood furniturezChina. 0aSustainable forestryzChina. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Environmental Policy.2bisacsh  abiodiversity.  acaptive breeding.  acritical theory.  acultural history.  adevelopment studies.  aethnography.  aforestry.  ageopolitics.  aglobal environmental governance.  aglobalization.  anatural resource management.  apolitical ecology.  areforestation.  awildlife trade.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311078579140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674276413?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps: